NOTES_MARK = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Archē" (G746) means "beginning" or "origin," echoing Genesis 1:1 (LXX). "Euangelion" (G2098) was used in the Roman world for imperial proclamations of victory or a new emperor\'s accession. Mark applies this politically charged term to Jesus, declaring him as the true sovereign. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "Son of God" (textually disputed but attested in major manuscripts including Sinaiticus corrector, Vaticanus) establishes Jesus\'s divine identity from the opening line — he is not merely the Christ, but the Son of God who shares in the divine nature.',
        2: 'TYPOLOGY: Mark attributes the composite quotation to Isaiah, though v2b draws from Malachi 3:1 (and possibly Exodus 23:20), while v3 comes from Isaiah 40:3. The Malachi passage concerns God sending his messenger before himself — Mark applies this to John preparing the way for Jesus, implying Jesus occupies the role of YHWH in the original prophecy. GREEK: "Kataskeuasei" (G2680) means "to prepare, construct, make ready" — the messenger\'s task is active preparation of the road for the coming King.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: Isaiah 40:3 in its original context announces YHWH\'s return to Zion through the wilderness. Mark applies "Lord" (kyrios, G2962) to Jesus — the one whose way John prepares is identified with the Lord God of Israel. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The voice crying in the wilderness recalls the heavenly herald announcing divine action; the wilderness motif connects to Israel\'s exodus and the expectation of a new exodus under God\'s direct kingship.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The contrast between water baptism and Spirit baptism marks the eschatological transition. John\'s baptism signifies repentance; Jesus\'s baptism in the Holy Spirit (pneumati hagiō, G4151 + G40) signifies the new covenant reality prophesied in Joel 2:28-29 and Ezekiel 36:26-27. The coming one does what only God can do — pour out the Spirit.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Schizomenous" (G4977) means "being torn, ripped apart" — Mark uses a violent participle, not merely "opened." This same root appears in Mark 15:38 when the temple veil is "torn" at Jesus\'s death, forming a literary inclusio. THEOLOGICAL: The tearing of the heavens fulfills Isaiah 64:1 ("Oh that you would tear the heavens and come down"). The barrier between heaven and earth is breached at Jesus\'s baptism. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Spirit descending and the heavenly voice together present a scene of the divine council commissioning the Son for his earthly mission.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: The heavenly voice combines Psalm 2:7 ("You are my Son") — a royal enthronement psalm — with Isaiah 42:1 ("my chosen one in whom my soul delights") — the Servant of the Lord. Jesus is simultaneously enthroned King and Suffering Servant. TYPOLOGY: The divine declaration at the Jordan parallels the anointing of Israel\'s kings, yet transcends it: this is not adoption language but the Father\'s eternal acknowledgment of the Son\'s identity and mission.',
        13: 'TYPOLOGY: The forty days echo Israel\'s forty years in the wilderness (Deut 8:2) and Moses\'s forty days on Sinai (Exod 34:28). Where Israel failed under testing, Jesus prevails. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Satan (G4567, "the Adversary") functions as the accuser from the divine council (cf. Job 1-2; Zech 3:1). The angels ministering (diēkonoun, G1247) to Jesus recalls Psalm 91:11-12 and portrays the faithful spiritual beings serving the Son, in contrast to the rebel adversary who tests him. The wild beasts may evoke the Edenic restoration theme (Isa 11:6-9).',
        15: 'GREEK: "Peplērōtai" (G4137) is a perfect passive — "has been fulfilled," indicating a completed divine action with ongoing results. "Kairos" (G2540) is not mere chronological time (chronos) but the divinely appointed, decisive moment. THEOLOGICAL: The kingdom of God (basileia tou theou) denotes God\'s active, sovereign reign breaking into the present age. The dual command "repent and believe" summarizes the proper human response to God\'s eschatological action in Christ.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The astonishment (exeplēssonto, G1605, "struck out of their senses") at Jesus\'s teaching reveals the unprecedented nature of his authority (exousia, G1849). Unlike the scribes who derived authority from tradition and citation of previous teachers, Jesus teaches as one possessing inherent authority — the authority of God himself. HISTORICAL: Scribes (grammateis, G1122) were the professional Torah scholars of Second Temple Judaism, experts in interpreting and transmitting the oral and written law.',
        24: 'GREEK: "Ti hēmin kai soi" is a Semitic idiom meaning "What have we to do with you?" — expressing a desire for separation and non-involvement. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The unclean spirit (pneuma akatharton) recognizes Jesus\'s true identity as "the Holy One of God" (ho hagios tou theou) — a title linking Jesus to divine holiness and the consecrated role of God\'s anointed agent. The demons\' supernatural knowledge of Jesus contrasts with human ignorance, a key theme in Mark\'s "messianic secret." The plural "us" may refer to the entire demonic realm that Jesus has come to overthrow.',
        34: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus silences the demons despite their correct identification of him. This "messianic secret" motif in Mark indicates that Jesus\'s identity cannot be rightly understood apart from the cross. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The demons\' knowledge of Jesus ("they knew him") reflects the spiritual realm\'s awareness of the divine Son\'s true identity and authority. Their forced obedience demonstrates that the kingdom of God is actively overthrowing the dominion of hostile spiritual powers.',
        38: 'GREEK: "Exēlthon" (G1831) — "I came forth" — carries theological weight beyond geographical movement. Jesus\'s mission originates from the Father; he "came forth" with divine purpose. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus refuses to be defined by popular demand. His mission is proclamation (kēryssō, G2784) of the kingdom, not merely miracle-working. The priority of the word over signs establishes the pattern for apostolic ministry.',
        41: 'GREEK: Some early manuscripts read "orgistheis" (G3710, "being angered") instead of "splanchnistheis" ("being moved with compassion"). If original, Jesus\'s anger may be directed at the disease itself, or at the ravaging effects of sin and death in creation. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s touching of the leper is extraordinary — contact with a leper rendered one ceremonially unclean (Lev 13:45-46). Instead of Jesus becoming unclean, his holiness and power reverse the flow: the unclean is made clean. This prefigures the new covenant reality where God\'s holiness is not defiled by contact with sinners but rather purifies them.',
        44: 'HISTORICAL: The command to show himself to the priest and offer the prescribed sacrifice follows Leviticus 14:1-32, the detailed ritual for cleansing from leprosy. "For a testimony to them" (eis martyrion autois) may mean as evidence to the priests that messianic healing has begun, or as a witness against their unbelief. TYPOLOGY: Jesus upholds the Mosaic law while simultaneously demonstrating authority that transcends it — he heals what only God can heal, then directs the healed man back to the Torah\'s prescribed order.',
    },
    2: {
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' declaration "your sins are forgiven" (ἀφίενταί σου αἱ ἁμαρτίαι) uses the divine passive, implying God as the agent of forgiveness. Yet Jesus speaks this on His own authority, which the scribes immediately recognize as a divine prerogative claim. The word τέκνον (teknon, "child") conveys tender affection beyond mere address. TYPOLOGY: This foreshadows the ultimate forgiveness accomplished at the cross (Isa 53:5; Col 2:13-14).',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The scribes\' reasoning is theologically correct in premise—only God can forgive sins (Isa 43:25; Ps 103:3)—but catastrophically wrong in conclusion. Their own logic, properly followed, should have led them to recognize Jesus\' divine identity. GREEK: βλασφημεῖ (blasphēmeí, Strong\'s G987) means to speak injuriously against God; the charge carried a death penalty under Torah (Lev 24:16).',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Son of Man" (ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ ἀνθρώπου) is Jesus\' primary self-designation, drawn from Daniel 7:13-14, where the Son of Man receives dominion, glory, and kingdom from the Ancient of Days. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The claim of ἐξουσία (exousía, "authority," Strong\'s G1849) to forgive sins "upon the earth" implies that heavenly authority is now operative on earth through the Son of Man—a direct echo of the Dan 7 enthronement scene. The healing serves as visible proof of the invisible forgiveness.',
        14: 'HISTORICAL: Levi son of Alphaeus is generally identified with Matthew the apostle (Matt 9:9). The τελώνιον (telṓnion, "tax booth," Strong\'s G5058) was a customs post likely on the Via Maris trade route near Capernaum. Tax collectors (τελῶναι) served Rome\'s interests and were despised as collaborators and ritually unclean by association with Gentiles. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' call of a tax collector demonstrates that the Kingdom breaks through social and religious boundaries of Second Temple purity expectations.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' physician metaphor reveals the mission of the Messiah: not to affirm the self-righteous but to bring healing to those who acknowledge their spiritual sickness. GREEK: δικαίους (dikaíous, "righteous," Strong\'s G1342) here carries ironic force—those who consider themselves righteous exclude themselves from the very salvation Jesus offers. This anticipates the Pauline doctrine that none are righteous in themselves (Rom 3:10, citing Ps 14:1-3).',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: The bridegroom (νυμφίος, nymphíos, Strong\'s G3566) imagery is a direct messianic claim. In the OT, YHWH is Israel\'s bridegroom (Isa 62:5; Hos 2:16-20). Jesus applies this title to Himself, identifying His presence with the eschatological wedding feast. The "sons of the bridechamber" (οἱ υἱοὶ τοῦ νυμφῶνος) is a Semitic idiom for wedding guests or attendants of the groom.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "taken away" (ἀπαρθῇ, aparthē, from ἀπαίρω, Strong\'s G522) is the first veiled prediction of Jesus\' violent death in Mark\'s Gospel. The verb carries connotations of forcible removal. This transforms fasting from mere ritual observance into an eschatological marker: mourning is appropriate only when the bridegroom is absent. TYPOLOGY: Echoes the Suffering Servant who is "cut off from the land of the living" (Isa 53:8).',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The twin parables of the unshrunk cloth and new wine declare that the kingdom Jesus brings cannot be contained within the existing structures of Second Temple Judaism. GREEK: νέον (néon) refers to wine "new" in time/age, while καινούς (kainoús) for the wineskins means "new" in quality or kind—a subtle distinction suggesting the eschatological newness of the kingdom (cf. 2 Cor 5:17). This is not mere reform but new creation.',
        26: 'HISTORICAL: The reference to Abiathar (Ἀβιαθάρ) as high priest presents a well-known difficulty, since 1 Samuel 21:1-6 names Ahimelech as the priest who gave David the bread. The Greek ἐπὶ Ἀβιαθὰρ ἀρχιερέως may mean "in the section concerning Abiathar" or "in the time of Abiathar" (who became the prominent high priest shortly after). TYPOLOGY: The bread of the Presence (ἄρτους τῆς προθέσεως, cf. Exod 25:30; Lev 24:5-9) typologically anticipates the Eucharistic bread—the true Presence of God given to those in need.',
        28: 'THEOLOGICAL: The climactic declaration that the Son of Man is κύριος (kýrios, "Lord," Strong\'s G2962) even of the Sabbath is a staggering authority claim. Since God instituted the Sabbath at creation (Gen 2:2-3) and commanded its observance (Exod 20:8-11), lordship over the Sabbath implies lordship held by the Creator Himself. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This verse, read alongside v.10, establishes a pattern in Mark 2: the Son of Man possesses divine prerogatives—forgiving sins (v.10) and sovereign authority over the Sabbath (v.28)—that belong to God alone in the OT framework.',
    },
    3: {
        2: 'GREEK: παρετήρουν (paratēreō, Strong\'s G3906) is imperfect tense, indicating continuous, hostile observation — "they kept watching closely." This verb carries connotations of malicious surveillance, not innocent observation. The Pharisees had already predetermined their verdict.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus frames the Sabbath question as a binary moral imperative: to do good (ἀγαθοποιῆσαι) or to do evil (κακοποιῆσαι), to save a soul (ψυχὴν σῶσαι) or to kill (ἀποκτεῖναι). His logic reveals that inaction in the face of suffering is itself evil. The irony is devastating: while Jesus heals on the Sabbath, the Pharisees plot murder (v. 6).',
        5: 'GREEK: πωρώσει (pōrōsis, Strong\'s G4457) means "hardness, petrification" — a calcification of the heart. This rare noun (also in Rom 11:25; Eph 4:18) conveys spiritual ossification beyond mere stubbornness. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus displays both divine anger (ὀργῆς) and compassionate grief (συλλυπούμενος) simultaneously — righteous wrath and sorrow coexisting, revealing the full emotional range of God incarnate.',
        6: 'HISTORICAL: The Pharisees and Herodians were natural enemies — the Pharisees resisted Hellenizing influence while the Herodians supported the Herodian dynasty and its Roman patronage. Their conspiracy against Jesus (cf. Mark 12:13) reveals that opposing factions unite when threatened by the kingdom of God. This alliance foreshadows the coalition that will ultimately crucify Him.',
        11: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The unclean spirits (πνεύματα ἀκάθαρτα) recognize Jesus as "the Son of God" (ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ) — a title with divine council significance. These rebellious spiritual beings recognize the identity that humans fail to perceive. Their forced prostration (προσέπιπτον) before Jesus demonstrates His sovereign authority over the spiritual realm (cf. Ps 82; Phil 2:10).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' stern silencing (ἐπετίμα, Strong\'s G2008) of the demons is part of Mark\'s "Messianic Secret" motif. Though the demons\' confession is factually true, Jesus will not receive His identity proclamation from unclean spirits. His messiahship must be revealed on His own terms — ultimately through the cross (Mark 15:39).',
        14: 'TYPOLOGY: The appointment of twelve (δώδεκα) deliberately echoes the twelve tribes of Israel. Jesus, ascending the mountain (v. 13) like Moses at Sinai, constitutes a renewed Israel around Himself. The verb ἐποίησεν ("He made/appointed") carries creative force — He is not merely selecting but constituting a new covenant community (cf. Ex 18:25; 1 Kgs 12:31).',
        27: 'TYPOLOGY: The parable of binding the strong one (ἰσχυρός) is a direct claim that Jesus\' exorcisms demonstrate Satan\'s defeat. Jesus is the one who enters the strong one\'s house, binds him, and plunders his possessions — liberating those held captive. This echoes Isaiah 49:24-25 where God promises to take spoil from the mighty. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This is a cosmic warfare text — Jesus claims authority to invade and dismantle Satan\'s domain.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: Blasphemy against the Holy Spirit (τὸ πνεῦμα τὸ ἅγιον) is the only sin declared unforgivable. The context (v. 30) defines this specifically: attributing the manifest work of the Holy Spirit to an unclean spirit. The phrase εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα ("unto the age") and αἰωνίου ἁμαρτήματος ("eternal sin") together indicate permanent, irrevocable guilt. GREEK: ἔνοχος (enochos, Strong\'s G1777) means "held in, liable to, guilty of" — a judicial term indicating binding culpability.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus radically redefines kinship around obedience to the will of God (τὸ θέλημα τοῦ θεοῦ) rather than biological descent. This is not a rejection of family but an elevation of spiritual union with God above all other bonds. This has profound implications for the new covenant community — membership in God\'s family is constituted by doing, not by bloodline (cf. John 1:12-13; Rom 8:14-17).',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Synágetai" (συνάγεται) is a historical present tense, giving vivid immediacy to the narrative—characteristic of Mark\'s style. "Pleistos" (πλεῖστος) is superlative of polýs, meaning "very greatest/largest." HISTORICAL: The Sea of Galilee\'s natural amphitheater shoreline would have amplified Jesus\'s voice from the boat, functioning as a natural teaching venue.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The sower parable echoes Isaiah 55:10-11 where God\'s word goes forth like rain and seed, accomplishing its purpose. The sower figure typologically points to Christ as the Word-bearer whose proclamation of the kingdom meets varied receptions. GREEK: "Speírōn" (σπείρων) is a present participle—"the one sowing"—used substantivally.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Mystērion" (μυστήριον, Strong\'s G3466) in Second Temple Jewish usage denotes a divine secret now revealed to the elect—cf. Daniel 2:28-29 LXX and 1QpHab 7:1-5 at Qumran. This is not esoteric mysticism but apocalyptic unveiling of God\'s purposes. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The distinction between insiders and outsiders reflects the divine council pattern where God\'s counsel is disclosed to his servants (Amos 3:7; Jer 23:18).',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: A direct quotation of Isaiah 6:9-10 LXX, from Isaiah\'s throne-room commission. The hardening motif echoes Pharaoh\'s hardening (Exod 4:21) and is taken up again in John 12:40 and Acts 28:26-27. THEOLOGICAL: The "hina" (ἵνα) clause indicates purpose, not mere result—a difficult but textually faithful rendering. Mark presents the parables as simultaneously revealing and concealing the kingdom\'s mystery.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Ton logon" (τὸν λόγον)—the word—is the seed. This identification of the sown seed with the proclaimed word of the kingdom establishes a pattern central to the New Testament: the gospel as living seed (1 Pet 1:23; Jas 1:21). Christ the Sower sows himself as the Logos (John 1:1).',
        19: 'GREEK: "Merimna" (μέριμνα, Strong\'s G3308) denotes anxious, divided care—from "merizō" (to divide). "Apatē" (ἀπάτη) is deceit or seduction. "Ákarpos" (ἄκαρπος, Strong\'s G175) means "without fruit," a significant negative in biblical theology where fruit-bearing marks covenant faithfulness (Isa 5:1-7). THEOLOGICAL: The three categories—cares of the age, deceitfulness of riches, desires for remaining things—form a comprehensive taxonomy of worldly distraction from the kingdom.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The hidden-revealed motif is central to Mark\'s messianic secret theme. What is presently concealed in parabolic form is destined for full apocalyptic disclosure. This anticipates the eschatological unveiling when the kingdom comes in fullness (Mark 9:1; Col 3:3-4). GREEK: "Apókryphon" (ἀπόκρυφον, Strong\'s G614)—"hidden away, concealed"—is the root of our word "apocryphal."',
        27: 'GREEK: "Mēkýnēται" (μηκύνηται) means "grows long, lengthens"—a rare word in the NT, appearing only here. THEOLOGICAL: The mystery of the seed\'s autonomous growth ("hōs ouk oiden autos"—"how, he himself does not know") emphasizes divine sovereignty over kingdom growth apart from human effort or comprehension. The kingdom advances by God\'s power, not human ingenuity.',
        29: 'TYPOLOGY: "Apostellei to drepanon" (sends forth the sickle) echoes Joel 3:13 LXX (4:13 MT): "Send forth the sickle, for the harvest has come." This is an eschatological harvest image pointing to final judgment and the gathering of God\'s people. GREEK: "Paradoi" (παραδοῖ) from paradídōmi—"yields, delivers up"—when the fruit presents/offers itself. The same verb is used for Jesus being "delivered up" to death (Mark 9:31; 10:33).',
        32: 'TYPOLOGY: The image of birds nesting in branches echoes Daniel 4:12 and Ezekiel 17:23; 31:6 LXX, where a great tree sheltering birds symbolizes a vast kingdom encompassing the nations. The mustard seed parable thus envisions the kingdom of God growing to encompass all peoples. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "birds of the heaven" (τὰ πετεινὰ τοῦ οὐρανοῦ) in prophetic imagery often represent the nations coming under God\'s sovereign rule.',
        39: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus rebukes (epitimáō, ἐπετίμησεν) the wind—the same verb used for rebuking demons (Mark 1:25; 3:12). "Phimóō" (πεφίμωσο, "be muzzled") is also used in the exorcism of Mark 1:25, suggesting cosmic authority over chaotic forces. TYPOLOGY: This scene echoes Psalm 89:9 (LXX 88:10) and Psalm 107:29 where God alone stills the sea and its waves—an unmistakable claim to divine identity. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Mastery over sea and storm is exclusively a divine prerogative in the Old Testament (Job 38:8-11; Ps 65:7; 104:7; Isa 51:15).',
        41: 'GREEK: "Ephobēthēsan phobon megan" (ἐφοβήθησαν φόβον μέγαν)—"they feared a great fear"—is a Semitic cognate accusative construction intensifying the verb. THEOLOGICAL: The disciples\' question "Tis ara houtos estin" ("Who then is this?") is the central Christological question of Mark\'s Gospel. That wind and sea "obey" (hypakoúei) him points to his divine identity, since in the Old Testament only YHWH commands the chaotic waters (Ps 33:7; 104:7; Nah 1:4). The expected answer: this is the God of Israel incarnate.',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: The "region of the Gerasenes" (Γερασηνῶν) places Jesus in predominantly Gentile territory east of the Sea of Galilee, part of the Decapolis. Textual variants include "Gadarenes" and "Gergesenes." This crossing into pagan land is theologically significant — the Lord of all extends his authority beyond Israel.',
        2: 'GREEK: ἐν πνεύματι ἀκαθάρτῳ (en pneumati akathartō) — literally "in an unclean spirit," denoting the man\'s condition of being dominated by the spirit. The preposition ἐν indicates the sphere of influence under which the man existed. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "unclean spirit" (πνεῦμα ἀκάθαρτον) designates a rebellious spiritual being opposed to God\'s holy order.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The demon\'s address "Son of the Most High God" (υἱὲ τοῦ θεοῦ τοῦ ὑψίστου) echoes the divine title El Elyon from Gen 14:18-20 and Ps 78:35. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The unclean spirit recognizes Jesus\'s unique status in the divine hierarchy — not merely a spirit-being but the Son of the supreme God above all powers. The verb ὁρκίζω (horkizō, Strong\'s G3726) means "I adjure/place under oath," an ironic reversal where the demonic attempts to invoke divine authority against the Divine Son himself.',
        9: 'GREEK: Λεγιών (Legiōn) is a Latin loanword (legio) transliterated into Greek, referring to a Roman military unit of approximately 4,000-6,000 soldiers. HISTORICAL: The use of a Roman military term for a demonic host in occupied territory carries overtones of imperial oppression — the man is occupied by a foreign legion, mirroring Israel\'s own subjugation. The shift from singular to plural ("we are many") reveals the corporate nature of the possession.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s authority over the unclean spirits is absolute — they cannot act without his permission (ἐπέτρεψεν, epitrepsen). The approximately two thousand swine destroyed underscores the magnitude of the demonic host. TYPOLOGY: The drowning of unclean beings in the sea echoes the destruction of Pharaoh\'s army in the Red Sea (Exod 14:27-28), a divine warrior motif where God\'s enemies perish in the waters.',
        19: 'GREEK: κύριος (kyrios) here is used by Jesus to refer to the Lord God, yet the healed man in v.20 proclaims what Jesus did for him — Mark thus equates the work of "the Lord" with the work of Jesus. THEOLOGICAL: This is a rare instance where Jesus commands proclamation rather than silence, notably in Gentile territory. The command to testify to "your own" (τοὺς σούς) makes the healed man the first Gentile evangelist in Mark\'s Gospel.',
        23: 'GREEK: ἐσχάτως ἔχει (eschatōs echei) — "is at the last / at the point of death," an adverbial construction with eschatological overtones. The verb σωθῇ (sōthē, from σῴζω, Strong\'s G4982) means both "be saved/healed" — Mark employs this word for both physical healing and spiritual salvation throughout the chapter (vv. 23, 28, 34).',
        28: 'THEOLOGICAL: The woman\'s statement σωθήσομαι ("I shall be saved/healed") uses the same root (σῴζω) as Jairus\'s plea in v.23. Mark interweaves both narratives around the theme of saving faith. TYPOLOGY: Her twelve-year affliction parallels the twelve years of Jairus\'s daughter\'s life (v.42), binding the two stories together as demonstrations of Christ\'s power over chronic suffering and death itself.',
        30: 'GREEK: δύναμις (dynamis, Strong\'s G1411) — "power/ability" — went out from Jesus. This is not magical or impersonal force but the active power of God working through the incarnate Son. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s awareness that power had gone forth (ἐξελθοῦσαν) demonstrates his conscious, sovereign exercise of divine authority even within the press of a crowd.',
        34: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Your faith has saved you" (ἡ πίστις σου σέσωκέν σε) — the perfect tense σέσωκεν indicates a completed action with abiding results. "Go into peace" (εἰς εἰρήνην) echoes the Hebrew לְשָׁלוֹם (leshalom), a covenantal blessing of wholeness (cf. 1 Sam 1:17). Jesus restores not only physical health but relational standing — addressing her as "Daughter" (θυγάτηρ) reintegrates her into the community from which her condition had excluded her (Lev 15:25-27).',
        36: 'GREEK: παρακούσας (parakoúsas, from παρακούω, Strong\'s G3878) can mean either "having overheard" or "having disregarded." Both senses work: Jesus either overhears the report of death, or deliberately disregards its implications. THEOLOGICAL: "Do not fear; only believe" (μὴ φοβοῦ, μόνον πίστευε) — the present imperative πίστευε demands continuous faith in the face of death\'s apparent finality.',
        41: 'GREEK: Ταλιθὰ κούμ is Aramaic (טַלִיתָא קוּמִי), preserved in Mark\'s Greek text — one of several Aramaic ipsissima verba of Jesus retained by Mark (cf. 7:34; 14:36; 15:34). THEOLOGICAL: Jesus speaks with direct creative authority over death itself. The command "Arise" (ἔγειρε, egeire) is the same verb used throughout the NT for resurrection (cf. Mark 16:6). Christ demonstrates lordship over the final enemy (1 Cor 15:26).',
        42: 'STRUCTURE: The detail that the girl was twelve years old (ἐτῶν δώδεκα) links her narratively with the woman who suffered twelve years (v.25). Mark\'s intercalation technique — sandwiching the bleeding woman\'s healing within the Jairus narrative — creates a literary and theological unity: both are "daughters" (vv. 23, 34), both involve the number twelve, and both are saved through encounter with Jesus. GREEK: ἐκστάσει μεγάλῃ — literally "with great ecstasy/astonishment," a dative of manner describing their overwhelming amazement.',
    },
    6: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Exeplēssonto" (ἐξεπλήσσοντο, from ekplēssō, Strong\'s G1605) means "struck out of one\'s senses" — a visceral astonishment beyond mere surprise. The imperfect tense suggests an ongoing state of amazement. "Dynameis" (δυνάμεις, G1411) refers to mighty works or acts of power, not merely "miracles" in the modern sense — it denotes the raw exercise of divine power.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Tektōn" (τέκτων, G5045) denotes a craftsman who works with hard materials — wood, stone, or metal. It is broader than the English "carpenter" and may indicate a builder or construction worker. HISTORICAL: In the Galilean village economy, a tektōn occupied a lower artisan class. The crowd\'s skandalon (offense) stems from the gulf between Jesus\' humble origins and His authoritative teaching and power.',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus identifies Himself within the prophetic tradition of Israel, echoing the pattern of rejected prophets such as Jeremiah (Jer 11:21) and Elijah (1 Kgs 19:2). This is the first explicit self-identification with prophetic rejection in Mark\'s Gospel, foreshadowing the ultimate rejection at Jerusalem.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The statement that Jesus "was not able" (ouk edynato, οὐκ ἐδύνατο) does not indicate a limitation of divine power but rather a self-imposed constraint. Faith is presented as the relational context in which divine power operates — not as a force that compels God, but as the posture that receives God\'s action. Cf. Matthew 13:58.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Apostéllein" (ἀποστέλλειν, G649) means to send forth with commission and authority, distinguishing it from "pémpō" (a general sending). The phrase "two by two" (dýo dýo) is a Semitic distributive idiom. THEOLOGICAL: The authority given over unclean spirits (pneumata akatharta) reflects the divine council framework in which delegated spiritual authority flows from the supreme King through His commissioned agents.',
        14: 'HISTORICAL: "King" (basileus) is used loosely of Herod Antipas, who was technically a tetrarch, not a king. Mark may use the title with irony, contrasting this petty ruler with Jesus, the true King. GREEK: "Energousin hai dynameis" — the powers "are at work" (energeō, G1754) in Him — reflects popular belief that a resurrected figure would possess enhanced supernatural power.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: John\'s declaration "it is not lawful" (ouk exestin) appeals to Leviticus 18:16 and 20:21, which prohibit marriage to a brother\'s wife (while the brother lives). John stands in the prophetic tradition of confronting royal sin, mirroring Elijah before Ahab (1 Kgs 21:17-24). TYPOLOGY: John as the forerunner of Messiah recapitulates Elijah\'s confrontation with corrupt Israelite royalty.',
        20: 'GREEK: "Synētērei" (συνετήρει, from syntēreō, G4933) means "was keeping safe" or "was preserving" — Herod functioned as a guardian of John even while imprisoning him. "Ēporei" (ἠπόρει, from aporeō, G639) indicates a state of being at a loss or perplexed, reflecting Herod\'s inner conflict. The imperfect tenses throughout portray an ongoing psychological tension.',
        21: 'GREEK: "Eukairou" (εὐκαίρου, from eukairos, G2121) means "opportune" or "well-timed" — used with dark irony, as the day is "opportune" for Herodias\'s plot. HISTORICAL: "Megistanes" (μεγιστᾶσιν, G3175) refers to the grandees or chief officials, while "chiliarchoi" (χιλίαρχοι) are military commanders over a thousand, indicating both civil and military elite attended.',
        27: 'GREEK: "Spekoulatōr" (σπεκουλάτωρ, G4688) is a Latin loanword (speculator) denoting a Roman military executioner or bodyguard — a hapax legomenon in the New Testament. Its use reflects the Romanized character of Herod\'s court. TYPOLOGY: The execution of the forerunner foreshadows the execution of the Messiah Himself — both at the hands of weak rulers manipulated by others.',
        34: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Esplanchnisthē" (ἐσπλαγχνίσθη, from splanchnizomai, G4697) denotes a visceral, gut-level compassion — the word derives from "splanchna" (entrails). TYPOLOGY: The image of sheep without a shepherd directly echoes Numbers 27:17 and Ezekiel 34:5, where God condemns Israel\'s failed shepherds and promises to shepherd His people Himself. Jesus, as the Good Shepherd-King, fulfills this divine promise (cf. Ezek 34:23; John 10:11).',
        41: 'TYPOLOGY: The sequence — taking, looking up to heaven, blessing, breaking, giving — prefigures the Last Supper (Mark 14:22) and the Eucharistic pattern of the early church. The feeding also recapitulates the wilderness manna provision (Exod 16), with Jesus acting in the role of YHWH who feeds His people. STRUCTURE: The twelve baskets correspond to the twelve tribes of Israel, symbolizing the restoration of the whole people of God under Messiah\'s provision.',
        43: 'GREEK: "Klasmata" (κλάσματα, G2801) are broken fragments, and "kophinōn" (κοφίνων, G2894) refers to wicker baskets specifically associated with Jewish travelers. THEOLOGICAL: The surplus of twelve full baskets after feeding five thousand demonstrates that Messiah\'s provision exceeds the need — a sign of the eschatological abundance promised in the prophets (Isa 25:6; Joel 2:26).',
        48: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Walking upon the sea" (peripatōn epi tēs thalassēs) evokes Job 9:8 LXX where God alone "walks upon the sea" and Psalm 77:19. The phrase "He was wanting to pass by them" (ēthelen parelthein) echoes the divine theophanies of Exodus 33:19-22 and 1 Kings 19:11, where YHWH "passes by." This is a deliberate divine self-revelation — Jesus acts in the identity of YHWH. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The sea in ancient Near Eastern cosmology represents chaos; to walk upon it is to exercise sovereign dominion over the forces of chaos, an act reserved for the Creator God alone.',
        50: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Egō eimi" (ἐγώ εἰμι) — "I am" — functions here both as simple self-identification and as a theophanic declaration echoing the divine Name of Exodus 3:14 (LXX: egō eimi ho ōn). Combined with walking on the sea and the "passing by" motif, this constitutes one of the most explicit divine identity claims in Mark\'s Gospel. The command "Fear not" (mē phobeisthe) is the characteristic divine reassurance in Old Testament theophanies (Isa 41:10, 43:1).',
        52: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pepōrōmenē" (πεπωρωμένη, from pōroō, G4456) means "hardened" or "petrified" — the perfect passive participle indicates a settled state of hardness. This is the same vocabulary used of Pharaoh\'s heart in the LXX tradition. Mark\'s editorial comment reveals that the feeding of the five thousand should have been sufficient to reveal Jesus\' divine identity, but the disciples\' hearts remained calloused. STRUCTURE: This forms a thematic bracket with Mark 8:17-21 where Jesus will directly confront their failure to understand the loaves.',
        56: 'GREEK: "Kraspedon" (κράσπεδον, G2899) refers to the tassel or fringe (Hebrew: tzitzit) required by Numbers 15:38-39 on the corners of one\'s garment — Jesus observed Torah faithfully. "Esōzonto" (ἐσῴζοντο, from sōzō, G4982) means "were being saved/healed" — the imperfect passive conveys an ongoing, repeated pattern. The word sōzō encompasses both physical healing and spiritual salvation, carrying the full weight of eschatological deliverance.',
    },
    7: {
        3: 'GREEK: The word πυγμῇ (pygmē, "with the fist") is unusual and debated—it likely refers to a specific manner of ritual handwashing, perhaps rubbing the fist into the open palm. Some take it as "diligently" or "up to the wrist." This parenthetical explanation (vv. 3–4) is Mark\'s editorial note for his Gentile audience unfamiliar with Jewish purity customs. HISTORICAL: The "tradition of the elders" (παράδοσιν τῶν πρεσβυτέρων) refers to the Oral Torah, later codified in the Mishnah, which Pharisees considered binding alongside written Scripture.',
        4: 'GREEK: The term βαπτίσωνται (baptisōntai, from βαπτίζω, Strong\'s G907) here refers to ritual immersion or ceremonial washing, not Christian baptism. The word ξεστῶν (xestōn) is a loanword from Latin sextarius, a liquid measure vessel—a rare borrowing indicating Roman cultural influence. HISTORICAL: These extensive purity regulations reflect Second Temple-era expansion of priestly holiness codes (Lev 11–15) to ordinary daily life, a distinctly Pharisaic program.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes Isaiah 29:13 (LXX), applying the prophet\'s rebuke of eighth-century Judah directly to the religious authorities of his day, establishing a pattern of prophetic indictment that transcends historical moment. THEOLOGICAL: The term ὑποκριτῶν (hypokritōn, "hypocrites," Strong\'s G5273) originally denoted a stage actor; Jesus applies it to those whose outward religious performance masks inward distance from God. The citation form ὡς γέγραπται ("as it is written") is a standard authoritative formula for Scripture.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The contrast between ἐντολὴν τοῦ θεοῦ ("commandment of God") and παράδοσιν τῶν ἀνθρώπων ("tradition of men") is the theological heart of the passage. Jesus asserts the absolute priority of divine command over human religious elaboration. This has profound implications for all subsequent ecclesial tradition—human tradition must never supplant or nullify divine revelation.',
        11: 'GREEK: Κορβᾶν (Korban) is a Hebrew/Aramaic loanword (קָרְבָּן) meaning "an offering" or "gift devoted to God" (Strong\'s G2878). Mark translates it for his Gentile readers as δῶρον ("gift"). HISTORICAL: The Corban vow allowed a person to declare property or money as dedicated to the Temple, thereby technically exempting it from use for parental support—a legal loophole that effectively circumvented the fifth commandment (Exod 20:12; Deut 5:16).',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse constitutes a revolutionary declaration regarding the nature of defilement. Jesus relocates the locus of impurity from external, ritual contact to the internal moral condition of the human heart. This teaching implicitly undermines the entire Levitical purity system as a means of achieving holiness before God, preparing the way for the inclusion of Gentiles (Acts 10:14–15).',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: The editorial comment καθαρίζων πάντα τὰ βρώματα ("thus cleansing all foods") is one of the most consequential parenthetical statements in the New Testament. Whether these are Mark\'s words or Jesus\' own, the declaration effectively abrogates the Levitical food laws (Lev 11; Deut 14), anticipating Peter\'s vision in Acts 10:9–16 and Paul\'s teaching in Romans 14:14,20. GREEK: The participle καθαρίζων is masculine nominative, grammatically awkward if modifying the neuter subject—suggesting it refers back to Jesus as the one who, by this pronouncement, cleanses all foods.',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: The term τέκνα ("children") refers to Israel, and κυνάρια ("little dogs," diminutive of κύων, Strong\'s G2952) to the Gentile nations. Jesus\' use of the diminutive softens but does not eliminate the ethnic distinction. The word πρῶτον ("first") is crucial—it implies a sequence, not an exclusion: Israel first, then the nations (Rom 1:16). TYPOLOGY: This exchange echoes the Abrahamic promise that through Israel all nations would be blessed (Gen 12:3; Gen 22:18).',
        32: 'GREEK: The word μογιλάλον (mogilalon, "hardly able to speak," Strong\'s G3424) is exceedingly rare—a near hapax in the NT, appearing elsewhere only in the LXX of Isaiah 35:6: "then shall the tongue of the mute (μογιλάλων) sing for joy." TYPOLOGY: This verbal echo strongly implies that Mark intends his readers to see Jesus\' healing as the fulfillment of Isaiah\'s eschatological vision of the messianic age, when the deaf hear and the mute speak (Isa 35:5–6).',
        34: 'GREEK: Εφφαθα (Ephphatha) is Aramaic (אתפתח), an ethpaal imperative meaning "be opened." Mark preserves the ipsissima vox ("very voice") of Jesus and translates for his audience with Διανοίχθητι. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' looking up to heaven (ἀναβλέψας εἰς τὸν οὐρανόν) and groaning (ἐστέναξεν) reveal both his dependence upon the Father and his deep compassion. The sovereign command-word that effects physical reality demonstrates divine authority resident in the incarnate Christ.',
        37: 'GREEK: The adverb ὑπερπερισσῶς ("beyond all measure," Strong\'s G5249) is a NT hapax legomenon, an intensified superlative expressing astonishment beyond the capacity of ordinary language. TYPOLOGY: The crowd\'s declaration Καλῶς πάντα πεποίηκεν ("He has done all things well") echoes Genesis 1:31 LXX (καλὰ λίαν, "very good"), casting Jesus as the Creator who restores the goodness of creation. The specific mention of the deaf hearing and the mute speaking directly fulfills Isaiah 35:5–6, confirming Jesus as the promised Messiah who inaugurates the new creation.',
    },
    8: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Splanchnizomai" (σπλαγχνίζομαι, Strong\'s G4697) denotes a visceral, gut-level compassion — literally a moving of the inward parts (splanchna). This term is used exclusively of Jesus and characters representing God in the parables, marking it as a divine attribute. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s compassion initiates the miracle, revealing the divine heart that provides for His people in the wilderness.',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: The disciples\' question echoes Israel\'s grumbling in the wilderness: "Can God spread a table in the wilderness?" (Ps 78:19). Despite having witnessed the feeding of the five thousand (Mark 6:35-44), they fail to perceive the pattern of divine provision through Christ, the new Moses.',
        8: 'GREEK: "Spyridas" (σπυρίδας, Strong\'s G4711) refers to large rope-baskets, distinct from the "kophinous" (κοφίνους, G2894) — smaller wicker baskets used in the feeding of the five thousand (6:43). Mark carefully preserves this distinction, as Jesus himself will reference it in vv. 19-20. THEOLOGICAL: Seven baskets of surplus after feeding Gentile territory may symbolize completeness of provision extending beyond Israel.',
        12: 'GREEK: "Anastenaxas" (ἀναστενάξας, G389) is a hapax legomenon in the NT — a deep, intensified groaning or sighing. The prefix "ana-" intensifies the verb. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "ei dothēsetai" ("if it shall be given") is a Semitic oath formula: "if a sign shall be given" means emphatically "no sign shall be given." This Hebrew idiom invokes an implied self-curse: "May God do such to me if..."',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Leaven" (zymē, G2219) in Jewish tradition symbolized permeating corruption. Jesus warns against the Pharisees\' hypocrisy and Herod\'s political pragmatism — both represent worldly systems opposed to the Kingdom of God. HISTORICAL: Herod Antipas ruled Galilee as tetrarch; combining him with the Pharisees represents the full spectrum of Israel\'s compromised leadership.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Pepōrōmenēn" (πεπωρωμένην, G4456) — a perfect passive participle meaning "having been hardened" or "petrified." Literally refers to the calcification of bone over a fracture, thus metaphorically a calloused, insensitive heart. TYPOLOGY: Jesus echoes the prophetic language of Isaiah 6:9-10 and Ezekiel 12:2, applying the same diagnosis of spiritual dullness that characterized rebellious Israel to his own disciples.',
        22: 'HISTORICAL: Bethsaida, located on the northeast shore of the Sea of Galilee, was the hometown of Philip, Andrew, and Peter (John 1:44). Philip the Tetrarch rebuilt it as "Julias." STRUCTURE: This healing of the blind man in two stages (unique to Mark) serves as a symbolic hinge in the Gospel — positioned between the disciples\' blindness (vv. 14-21) and Peter\'s partial sight at Caesarea Philippi (v. 29). Spiritual sight, like physical sight here, comes progressively.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: Peter\'s confession "Su ei ho Christos" — "You are the Christ" — is the climactic turning point of Mark\'s Gospel. "Christos" (Χριστός, G5547) translates Hebrew "Mashiach" (Anointed One), the promised Davidic King (2 Sam 7:12-16; Ps 2:2; Dan 9:25-26). Peter rightly identifies Jesus\'s identity but, as vv. 32-33 will reveal, profoundly misunderstands the nature of His messianic mission.',
        31: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is the first of three Passion predictions in Mark (8:31; 9:31; 10:33-34). "Dei" (δεῖ, G1163) — "it is necessary" — indicates divine necessity, not mere human fate. The Son of Man "must" suffer according to the determined counsel of God. TYPOLOGY: "The Son of Man" (ho huios tou anthrōpou) draws from Daniel 7:13-14, where the figure receives an everlasting kingdom — yet Jesus radically redefines this through the path of suffering, merging Daniel\'s exalted figure with the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 53.',
        33: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Hypage opisō mou, Satana" — "Get behind me, Satan!" Jesus identifies Peter\'s rebuke as satanic opposition to the divine plan. "Satanas" (Σατανᾶς, G4567), transliterated from Hebrew "ha-satan," designates the adversary. Peter unwittingly assumes the role of the accuser by opposing God\'s redemptive purpose through the cross. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The cosmic conflict surfaces here — Satan\'s strategy, whether through direct temptation (1:13) or through a well-meaning disciple, is to divert the Messiah from the cross.',
        34: 'GREEK: "Aparnesasthō heauton" (ἀπαρνησάσθω ἑαυτόν) — "let him deny himself" — uses the same verb (aparneomai, G533) that will describe Peter\'s denial of Jesus (14:30-31, 72). The irony is profound: Peter who refuses to accept a suffering Messiah will himself fail at the very self-denial Jesus here requires. THEOLOGICAL: The cross (stauros, G4716) was not yet a religious symbol but an instrument of Roman execution and public shame — Jesus\'s call is radically literal.',
        38: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Son of Man" who must suffer (v. 31) will also come "in the glory of his Father with the holy angels" — a clear allusion to Daniel 7:13-14 and the divine council assembly. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "holy angels" (tōn angelōn tōn hagiōn) constitute the heavenly host — members of the divine council (cf. Deut 33:2; Ps 89:5-7; Zech 14:5). The Son of Man arrives not merely as a human figure but as the one who shares the Father\'s glory and commands the heavenly armies, exercising the prerogative of divine judgment.',
    },
    9: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: This solemn "Amen" declaration connects to the Transfiguration that immediately follows. The kingdom of God "having come in power" (ἐληλυθυῖαν ἐν δυνάμει, elelythuian en dynamei — perfect participle indicating completed arrival) likely finds its initial fulfillment in the Transfiguration vision of vv. 2-8, where three disciples witness the glorified Christ. The double negative οὐ μή (ou mē) is the strongest form of negation in Greek.',
        2: 'TYPOLOGY: The "six days" echoes Moses ascending Sinai after six days of cloud-covering (Exod 24:16). The three chosen witnesses parallel the requirement of testimony by two or three witnesses (Deut 19:15). GREEK: μετεμορφώθη (metemorphōthē, from metamorphóō, Strong\'s G3339) — a divine passive indicating God as the agent of transformation. The same root appears in Rom 12:2 and 2 Cor 3:18.',
        3: 'GREEK: στίλβοντα (stilbonta) — "glistening, gleaming," a vivid term suggesting radiant, flashing brightness. THEOLOGICAL: The supernatural whiteness beyond any earthly fuller\'s ability signals the breaking through of heavenly glory into the earthly realm, a theophanic marker (cf. Dan 7:9; Rev 1:14).',
        5: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter\'s proposal to build three σκηνάς (skēnas, "tabernacles/tents") evokes the Feast of Tabernacles (Lev 23:42-43) and the Tent of Meeting where God\'s presence dwelt. By placing Jesus alongside Moses and Elijah as equals, Peter misunderstands Christ\'s unique supremacy — a misunderstanding corrected by the divine voice in v. 7.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The cloud (νεφέλη, nephelē) is the shekinah glory-cloud of God\'s presence (Exod 40:34-35). The voice from the cloud echoes Ps 2:7 ("my Son"), Isa 42:1 ("the Beloved"), and Deut 18:15 ("hear him"), identifying Jesus as the royal Son, the chosen Servant, and the Prophet greater than Moses. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Father speaks from the heavenly dimension, publicly commissioning the Son before witnesses, establishing his supreme authority over all prophetic and legal revelation.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: The command to silence "until the Son of Man should rise from the dead" (ἐκ νεκρῶν ἀναστῇ) indicates that the Transfiguration can only be rightly understood in light of the resurrection. The title "Son of Man" (ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ ἀνθρώπου) draws on Dan 7:13-14, where the figure receives everlasting dominion from the Ancient of Days.',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus affirms Elijah\'s eschatological role of restoration (ἀποκαθιστάνει πάντα, apokathistanei panta, cf. Mal 4:5-6) while simultaneously redirecting attention to the suffering of the Son of Man. GREEK: ἐξουδενηθῇ (exoudenēthē) — "be treated as nothing, utterly despised" — a rare intensified form pointing to Isa 53:3 and Ps 22:6. The juxtaposition of Elijah\'s restoration with the Son of Man\'s suffering reveals the paradox of messianic fulfillment.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s exclamation Ὦ γενεὰ ἄπιστος (Ō genea apistos, "O faithless generation") echoes Moses\'s frustration with Israel in the wilderness (Deut 32:5, 20). The questions "how long shall I be with you?" foreshadow his departure through death. His rebuke encompasses not merely the disciples but the entire generation characterized by unbelief.',
        23: 'GREEK: Jesus quotes the father\'s own conditional "if you are able" (τὸ εἰ δύνῃ, to ei dynē) and turns it back — the issue is not Christ\'s power but the father\'s faith. THEOLOGICAL: πάντα δυνατὰ τῷ πιστεύοντι (panta dynata tō pisteuonti) — "all things are possible to the one who believes" — does not make faith a magical force but identifies trust in Christ as the channel through which divine power operates.',
        24: 'GREEK: The paradox "I believe; help my unbelief!" (πιστεύω· βοήθει μου τῇ ἀπιστίᾳ) is one of the most theologically profound statements in the Gospels. The present imperative βοήθει (boēthei) indicates ongoing help needed. THEOLOGICAL: Faith is here presented not as a human achievement but as a gift that must be supplemented by divine aid — honest confession of inadequacy becomes itself an act of faith.',
        25: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Jesus commands the unclean spirit with direct personal authority: ἐγὼ ἐπιτάσσω σοι (egō epitassō soi, "I myself command you"). The emphatic pronoun ἐγώ asserts his sovereign authority over hostile spiritual beings. GREEK: ἄλαλον καὶ κωφὸν πνεῦμα (alalon kai kōphon pneuma) — the spirit is characterized by the symptoms it inflicts: "mute and deaf." The permanent banishment ("enter into him no more") demonstrates Christ\'s absolute authority over the demonic realm.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: The declaration that "this kind" (τοῦτο τὸ γένος, touto to genos) requires prayer reveals that certain confrontations with evil demand a deeper dependence on God. Some manuscripts add "and fasting" (καὶ νηστείᾳ), though this is likely a later scribal addition. The point is radical reliance upon divine power rather than presumed spiritual competence.',
        31: 'STRUCTURE: This is the second of three passion predictions in Mark (8:31; 9:31; 10:33-34), each followed by misunderstanding and teaching on discipleship. GREEK: παραδίδοται (paradidotai) — present passive, "is being delivered," suggesting an already-unfolding divine plan. The passive voice implies God as the ultimate agent behind the handing over (cf. Isa 53:6, 10; Rom 8:32).',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus inverts the world\'s power structure: the one desiring to be πρῶτος (prōtos, "first") must become ἔσχατος (eschatos, "last") and διάκονος (diakonos, "servant/minister," Strong\'s G1249). This is not mere moral instruction but a revelation of the character of God\'s kingdom, modeled by Jesus himself who came to serve (Mark 10:45).',
        37: 'THEOLOGICAL: Receiving a child "in my name" (ἐπὶ τῷ ὀνόματί μου) means receiving one who has no social power or status, thereby reflecting God\'s own values. The chain of identification — child to Christ to the Father ("the One who sent me," τὸν ἀποστείλαντά με) — establishes that how one treats the least reveals one\'s relationship to God himself. TYPOLOGY: This anticipates the judgment scene of Matt 25:40.',
        42: 'GREEK: σκανδαλίσῃ (skandalisē, from skandalízō, Strong\'s G4624) means "to cause to stumble" or "to ensnare." The μύλος ὀνικός (mylos onikos) is literally a "donkey millstone" — the large upper stone turned by a donkey, far heavier than a hand-mill stone. THEOLOGICAL: The severity of the warning reveals the gravity with which Christ regards the spiritual care of vulnerable believers.',
        48: 'TYPOLOGY: A direct quotation of Isa 66:24 (LXX), describing the final fate of those who rebel against God. In its Isaianic context, this is the concluding vision of the new heavens and new earth, where the righteous look upon the judgment of the wicked. GREEK: σκώληξ (skōlēx, "worm") and the unquenched fire together depict the permanence and irreversibility of divine judgment.',
        49: 'GREEK: ἁλισθήσεται (halisthēsetai, from halízō, "to salt," Strong\'s G233) — a difficult and much-debated saying. THEOLOGICAL: Fire and salt both serve as purifying and preserving agents. Every disciple will be tested and purified through suffering (cf. 1 Pet 1:6-7; 4:12). The connection to the preceding Gehenna warnings suggests that while fire destroys the unrepentant, it purifies the faithful.',
        50: 'GREEK: ἄναλον (analon) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "without salt, unsalty" — a paradoxical concept since salt (sodium chloride) cannot technically lose its saltness, but Palestinian salt mixed with impurities could leach out. THEOLOGICAL: Salt represents the distinctive character of discipleship; losing it renders one useless to God\'s purposes. The closing imperative εἰρηνεύετε ἐν ἀλλήλοις ("be at peace with one another") returns to the dispute of v. 34, showing that humble service and mutual peace are the true marks of kingdom life.',
    },
    10: {
        2: 'GREEK: The verb πειράζοντες (peirázontes, Strong\'s G3985) means "testing" or "tempting," revealing the Pharisees\' hostile intent. Their question about divorce aimed to trap Jesus between rival rabbinic schools (Shammai vs. Hillel) or to provoke Him regarding Herod Antipas\'s unlawful marriage, which had led to John the Baptist\'s execution. HISTORICAL: In Second Temple Judaism, debate centered on Deuteronomy 24:1 — Shammai permitted divorce only for sexual immorality, while Hillel allowed it for virtually any cause.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus appeals past the Mosaic concession directly to the creation order (Gen 1:27), establishing that God\'s original design for marriage precedes and supersedes the Deuteronomic provision. This hermeneutical move — from Torah to creation — asserts His authority as the One who was present at the beginning. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase ἀπὸ δὲ ἀρχῆς κτίσεως (apo de archēs ktiseōs) links to Gen 1:1 LXX and positions Jesus as the authoritative interpreter of the Creator\'s intent.',
        9: 'GREEK: συνέζευξεν (synézeyxen, Strong\'s G4801) means "yoked together" or "joined together," a compound of σύν (together) and ζεύγνυμι (to yoke). The image is of two oxen placed under one yoke — a permanent, divinely ordered union. THEOLOGICAL: By declaring that God is the active agent in marriage, Jesus elevates the covenant from a mere legal contract to an act of divine sovereignty that no human authority may dissolve.',
        14: 'GREEK: ἠγανάκτησεν (ēganáktēsen, Strong\'s G23) denotes strong emotional indignation — one of the rare moments Mark records Jesus expressing visible anger on behalf of the vulnerable. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase τῶν γὰρ τοιούτων ἐστὶν ἡ βασιλεία τοῦ θεοῦ ("for of such is the kingdom of God") does not sentimentalize childhood but identifies the posture of dependence, lack of social status, and receptivity as the mode of kingdom entry.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The double negative οὐ μή (ou mē) with the subjunctive εἰσέλθῃ is the strongest negation possible in Greek — "shall by absolutely no means enter." Receiving the kingdom ὡς παιδίον ("as a child") means receiving it as one who has no merit, no claim, no leverage — pure receptivity. This undermines all systems of earned righteousness.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' response "Why do you call Me good? No one is good except One — God" is not a denial of His divinity but a Socratic challenge: if only God is truly good, and the man calls Jesus good, what does that imply about who Jesus is? Jesus presses the man toward a deeper confession than mere flattery. GREEK: ἀγαθός (agathós, Strong\'s G18) here denotes inherent, essential goodness — a quality belonging properly to God alone.',
        21: 'GREEK: ἐμβλέψας (emblépsas, Strong\'s G1689) means "having looked intently into" — a penetrating gaze, not a casual glance. Mark uniquely records that Jesus ἠγάπησεν αὐτόν ("loved him," from agapáō, G25), the only time in the Gospels this is said of Jesus toward a specific individual in a narrative encounter. THEOLOGICAL: The demand to sell all possessions is not a universal command but a diagnostic exposing this man\'s ultimate allegiance — his wealth functioned as his true god.',
        25: 'GREEK: κάμηλον (kámēlon, Strong\'s G2574) is "camel," and τρυμαλιᾶς τῆς ῥαφίδος (trymaliâs tēs rhaphídos) is "eye of a needle" — a literal sewing needle, not a supposed small gate (a medieval invention with no historical basis). Jesus intends an impossibility to demonstrate that salvation cannot be achieved by human effort or wealth. HISTORICAL: In rabbinic literature, a similar expression about an elephant through a needle\'s eye conveyed the same hyperbolic impossibility.',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: The statement παρὰ ἀνθρώποις ἀδύνατον ἀλλ\' οὐ παρὰ θεῷ ("with men impossible, but not with God") is the theological hinge of the entire passage. Salvation is entirely a divine act — no amount of human wealth, moral effort, or religious observance can achieve it. This echoes Genesis 18:14 LXX and Jeremiah 32:17, where God\'s power transcends all human limitation (cf. Job 42:2).',
        30: 'GREEK: ἑκατονταπλασίονα (hekatontaplasíona, Strong\'s G1542) means "a hundredfold" — an extravagant, superabundant return. Crucially, Mark includes μετὰ διωγμῶν ("with persecutions"), a sober addition absent from the parallel in Matthew, reflecting Mark\'s pastoral context of a persecuted community likely in Rome. THEOLOGICAL: The promise is not prosperity theology but a new family — the ἐκκλησία — that provides brothers, sisters, mothers, and fields within the messianic community, accompanied by the cost of discipleship.',
        33: 'TYPOLOGY: This is the third and most detailed passion prediction in Mark (cf. 8:31, 9:31). The specificity increases each time — here Jesus names the chief priests, scribes, Gentiles, and details mocking, spitting, scourging, killing, and rising. The progression echoes Isaiah 50:6 and anticipates Isaiah 53. STRUCTURE: Mark places this prediction immediately after the promise of hundredfold reward, linking the path to glory with the path through suffering.',
        38: 'GREEK: ποτήριον (potḗrion, Strong\'s G4221), "cup," is a well-established OT metaphor for divine judgment and wrath that one must drink (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17, 22; Jer 25:15). βάπτισμα (báptisma, Strong\'s G908), "baptism," here metaphorically denotes overwhelming immersion in suffering and death. TYPOLOGY: Jesus uses both images — cup and baptism — to describe His approaching passion, linking His death to the prophetic tradition of bearing the cup of God\'s wrath on behalf of His people.',
        42: 'GREEK: κατακυριεύουσιν (katakyrieúousin, Strong\'s G2634) means "lord it over" or "exercise dominion over" — the κατα- prefix intensifies the verb, suggesting oppressive, top-down domination. Similarly, κατεξουσιάζουσιν (katexousiázousin, G2715) means "wield authority over" in an exploitative manner. HISTORICAL: This directly critiques the Roman imperial system of patronage and domination familiar to Mark\'s audience, likely in Rome under Nero.',
        45: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is the theological summit of Mark\'s Gospel. The Son of Man — the exalted figure of Daniel 7:13-14 who receives dominion and a kingdom — came not to be served (διακονηθῆναι) but to serve (διακονῆσαι). GREEK: λύτρον (lýtron, Strong\'s G3083) is "ransom" — the price paid to release a slave or captive. ἀντί (antí, Strong\'s G473) means "in the place of" or "in exchange for," indicating substitutionary atonement. This echoes Isaiah 53:10-12, where the Servant gives His life as an \'āšām (guilt offering) for the many.',
        47: 'THEOLOGICAL: Bartimaeus\' cry Υἱὲ Δαυίδ ("Son of David") is an explicitly messianic title drawn from the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16; Isa 11:1; Jer 23:5). A blind beggar perceives what the sighted fail to see — that Jesus is the promised Davidic King. TYPOLOGY: The healing of blindness fulfills Isaiah 35:5 and 42:7, messianic-age signs that the Lord\'s Anointed has come to restore sight to the blind, both physically and spiritually.',
        52: 'GREEK: σέσωκέν (sésōkén) is the perfect tense of σῴζω (sṓzō, Strong\'s G4982), meaning both "has healed" and "has saved" — Mark intentionally preserves this dual meaning. The faith (πίστις, pístis) that heals Bartimaeus physically also saves him eschatologically. STRUCTURE: Bartimaeus immediately ἠκολούθει αὐτῷ ἐν τῇ ὁδῷ ("was following Him on the road") — the road to Jerusalem and the cross. He becomes the paradigmatic disciple: blind, then seeing, then following Jesus on the way of suffering. This closes the central section of Mark that began with another blind healing at Bethsaida (8:22-26).',
    },
    11: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: Bethphage ("house of unripe figs") and Bethany ("house of affliction/dates") were villages on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, approximately two miles from Jerusalem. TYPOLOGY: The Mount of Olives holds eschatological significance; Zechariah 14:4 prophesies the Lord will stand upon it in the day of judgment. Jesus\' deliberate approach from this direction signals messianic fulfillment.',
        2: 'GREEK: πῶλον (pōlon, G4454) refers to a young animal, specifically a young donkey. The detail that no one had ever sat upon it (ἐφ\' ὃν οὐδεὶς οὔπω ἀνθρώπων ἐκάθισεν) indicates consecrated, unused status—animals dedicated to sacred purposes were to be unyoked (Num 19:2; Deut 21:3; 1 Sam 6:7). TYPOLOGY: This directly fulfills Zechariah 9:9, where the messianic King comes riding on a colt, the foal of a donkey—humble yet royal.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' self-designation as ὁ κύριος (ho kyrios, "the Lord") here carries weight beyond mere courtesy. In this context it asserts sovereign ownership and divine right—the Lord has need of what is already his. This echoes Psalm 24:1, "The earth is the Lord\'s and its fullness."',
        9: 'GREEK: Ὡσαννά (hōsanna) is a transliteration of Hebrew הוֹשִׁיעָה נָּא (hoshia-na, "Save, we pray!") from Psalm 118:25-26. TYPOLOGY: Psalm 118 was a Hallel psalm sung during Feast of Tabernacles and Passover. "Blessed is the one coming in the name of the Lord" (Ps 118:26) was understood messianically in Second Temple Judaism. The crowd\'s acclamation identifies Jesus as the awaited Davidic King.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "the coming kingdom of our father David" explicitly links Jesus\' entry to the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16). "Hosanna in the highest" directs the cry of salvation to the heavenly realm itself, acknowledging that this deliverance originates from God\'s throne. This is a public declaration of Jesus as Messiah-King.',
        14: 'GREEK: εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα (eis ton aiōna, "unto the age") denotes permanence—"never again, unto eternity." TYPOLOGY: The cursing of the fig tree functions as a prophetic sign-act (cf. Jer 24:1-10; Hos 9:10, 16). Israel, and specifically the temple establishment, is the fig tree bearing leaves (outward religious appearance) but no fruit. This brackets the temple cleansing (vv.15-17) in a Markan "sandwich" structure, interpreting each event through the other.',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: The outer Court of the Gentiles had become a marketplace for sacrificial animals and currency exchange (Roman coinage bearing idolatrous images had to be exchanged for Tyrian shekels for the temple tax). κολλυβιστῶν (kollybistōn, G2855) refers specifically to money-changers who charged exchange fees. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus acts with the authority of the temple\'s true Lord, cleansing his Father\'s house—an implicit claim to divine prerogative over the sacred space.',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus combines Isaiah 56:7 ("My house shall be called a house of prayer for all the nations") with Jeremiah 7:11 ("den of robbers"). The Isaiah citation emphasizes God\'s universal purpose—the temple was meant for all nations, not exclusive commerce. The Jeremiah citation recalls Jeremiah\'s temple sermon, which warned of the destruction of the first temple for similar corruption. Jesus implies this temple faces the same judgment. STRUCTURE: This verse forms the theological center of the Markan fig tree sandwich (vv.12-14, 15-19, 20-21).',
        22: 'GREEK: πίστιν θεοῦ (pistin theou) is literally "faith of God." The genitive θεοῦ is typically understood as an objective genitive: "faith directed toward God." However, the construction is unusual and may also carry the sense of "God-quality faith"—a faith that participates in divine power. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus grounds the disciples\' capacity for prayer and spiritual authority in radical trust in God himself.',
        23: 'THEOLOGICAL: The mountain cast into the sea may allude to the Mount of Olives or the Temple Mount itself, carrying eschatological overtones (cf. Zech 14:4). The condition μὴ διακριθῇ (mē diakrithē, "does not doubt/waver," G1252) denotes internal division of mind. Faith here is presented not as psychological certainty but as undivided allegiance to God\'s word and power.',
        25: 'THEOLOGICAL: Forgiveness is presented as a prerequisite for effective prayer, linking the vertical relationship with God to horizontal relationships with others. The phrase ὁ πατὴρ ὑμῶν ὁ ἐν τοῖς οὐρανοῖς ("your Father who is in the heavens") echoes Matthean language (Matt 6:14-15) and grounds the command in God\'s fatherly character. Note: Many manuscripts include a verse 26 paralleling Matt 6:15, but the earliest and best manuscripts of Mark omit it.',
        30: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' counter-question is not evasion but a masterful exposure of his opponents\' bad faith. The baptism of John and the authority of Jesus stand or fall together, since John bore witness to Jesus as the Coming One (John 1:29-34). If John\'s authority was from heaven, then his testimony about Jesus validates Jesus\' authority. HISTORICAL: The Sanhedrin delegation (chief priests, scribes, elders) represents the full Jewish ruling council challenging Jesus\' right to act in the temple precinct.',
    },
    12: {
        1: 'TYPOLOGY: The parable of the vineyard directly echoes Isaiah 5:1-7, where Israel is God\'s vineyard. Jesus recasts the Song of the Vineyard to indict Israel\'s leaders as wicked tenants, with God as the owner who sends prophets (servants) and finally his own Son. GREEK: ἀμπελῶνα (ampelōna, G290) — "vineyard," a loaded term evoking covenant identity. ὑπολήνιον (hypolēnion, G5276) — "wine vat" or pit beneath the winepress; a hapax legomenon in the NT.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase ἕνα υἱὸν ἀγαπητόν (hena huion agapēton, "one beloved son") directly parallels the divine voice at Jesus\'s baptism (Mark 1:11) and transfiguration (Mark 9:7). This identifies the parabolic son with Jesus himself and signals the Father\'s unique, unrepeatable sending of the Son. TYPOLOGY: The "beloved son" echoes Isaac in Genesis 22:2 (LXX: τὸν ἀγαπητόν), connecting Jesus\'s death to the Aqedah.',
        10: 'TYPOLOGY: Quotation of Psalm 118:22-23 (LXX 117:22-23). The rejected stone becoming the cornerstone is a messianic proof-text applied to Jesus\'s rejection by Israel\'s leaders and his vindication through resurrection (cf. Acts 4:11; 1 Pet 2:7). GREEK: κεφαλὴν γωνίας (kephalēn gōnias) — "head of the corner," the capstone or cornerstone that holds the entire structure together.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: ἀπόδοτε (apodote, G591) means "give back" or "render" — implying that what bears Caesar\'s image belongs to Caesar, but what bears God\'s image (humanity itself, Gen 1:26-27) belongs to God. The statement transcends a mere political answer, making a radical claim about divine ownership of all persons. HISTORICAL: The κῆνσος (kēnsos, G2778) was the Roman poll-tax, deeply resented in Judea and the catalyst for Judas the Galilean\'s revolt in AD 6.',
        25: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: ὡς ἄγγελοι ἐν τοῖς οὐρανοῖς (hōs angeloi en tois ouranois) — "as angels in the heavens." Jesus affirms the reality of heavenly beings (members of the divine council) and indicates the resurrected state is a transformed, embodied existence comparable to angelic beings (cf. 1 Cor 15:42-49). This is not disembodiment but glorified, non-procreative existence. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus corrects the Sadducees\' materialistic reduction of resurrection by pointing to God\'s transformative power (δύναμις τοῦ θεοῦ, v.24).',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus argues for resurrection from the Torah itself (Exod 3:6), the only portion the Sadducees fully accepted. The present tense "I am" (ἐγώ... θεός) implies Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob are living to God — God\'s covenant faithfulness demands their resurrection. GREEK: ἐπὶ τοῦ βάτου (epi tou batou) — "at the bush," a section-reference to the Exodus passage, showing early methods of citing Scripture before chapter-and-verse divisions.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus quotes the Shema (Deut 6:4-5), the foundational confession of Israel\'s faith. κύριος ὁ θεὸς ἡμῶν κύριος εἷς ἐστιν — "The Lord our God, the Lord is one." This affirms strict monotheism while the surrounding context (vv.35-37) identifies Jesus as the Lord seated at God\'s right hand, pressing the question of Jesus\'s divine identity within the framework of Israel\'s one God. STRUCTURE: The pairing of Deut 6:4-5 with Lev 19:18 (v.31) as the two greatest commandments forms the ethical-theological center of Mark\'s Gospel.',
        36: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Quotation of Psalm 110:1 (LXX 109:1) — Εἶπεν κύριος τῷ κυρίῳ μου — "The Lord said to my Lord." The first κύριος represents YHWH; the second κυρίῳ μου is David\'s "Lord," the enthroned messianic king at God\'s right hand. Jesus uses this to demonstrate that the Messiah is not merely David\'s descendant but David\'s sovereign Lord, implying a divine status that transcends Davidic lineage. GREEK: ἐν τῷ πνεύματι τῷ ἁγίῳ (en tō pneumati tō hagiō) — "by the Holy Spirit," affirming divine inspiration of the Psalms and David\'s prophetic role.',
        40: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus pronounces eschatological judgment on the scribes: περισσότερον κρίμα (perissoteron krima) — "greater condemnation." The exploitation of widows under the guise of piety constitutes a particularly grievous sin because it violates both the love-of-neighbor command and the prophetic demand for justice (Isa 1:17; Jer 7:6). HISTORICAL: Scribes could serve as estate trustees for widows; abuse of this role was a documented problem in Second Temple Judaism.',
        42: 'GREEK: λεπτά δύο (lepta dyo) — two lepta (G3016), the smallest copper coins in circulation, worth 1/128 of a denarius. Mark explains for his Roman audience: ὅ ἐστιν κοδράντης (ho estin kodrantēs, G2835), "which is a quadrans," the smallest Roman coin. TYPOLOGY: The widow\'s total self-giving prefigures Jesus\'s own offering of his whole life (Mark 10:45; 14:22-24). She embodies the total devotion of the Shema (v.30) that the scribes merely profess.',
        44: 'THEOLOGICAL: ὅλον τὸν βίον αὐτῆς (holon ton bion autēs) — "her whole livelihood," literally "her whole life." The word βίος (bios, G979) denotes not merely money but means of living. Her gift is an act of radical trust in God as provider. STRUCTURE: This episode closes the temple section of Mark and transitions to the Olivet Discourse (ch.13), where Jesus prophesies the temple\'s destruction — the very institution to which she gave everything.',
    },
    13: {
        2: 'GREEK: The double negative οὐ μὴ (ou mē) with the aorist subjunctive ἀφεθῇ (aphethē, from ἀφίημι, Strong\'s G863) and καταλυθῇ (katalythē, from καταλύω, G2647, "to throw down, demolish") expresses the strongest possible negation in Greek—an emphatic prophetic declaration of total destruction. HISTORICAL: This prophecy was fulfilled in AD 70 when Titus\'s Roman legions razed the Second Temple, dismantling it stone by stone to extract the gold that had melted between the stones during the fire.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus sits on the Mount of Olives opposite the temple, evoking Ezekiel 11:23 where the glory of the Lord departs from the temple and stands on the mountain east of the city. The Olivet setting frames the discourse as a prophetic oracle concerning the temple\'s judgment. HISTORICAL: The inner circle of Peter, James, John, and Andrew—the first four called (Mark 1:16-20)—receive this teaching privately (κατ\' ἰδίαν, kat\' idian), a pattern in Mark for revelations about the messianic mission.',
        8: 'GREEK: ὠδίνων (ōdinōn, Strong\'s G5604) means "birth pains," a term drawn from OT prophetic imagery (Isa 26:17; Jer 22:23; Mic 4:9-10). The word ἀρχή (archē, "beginning") indicates these catastrophes inaugurate rather than conclude the eschatological travail. THEOLOGICAL: In Second Temple Jewish apocalyptic literature, the "birth pains of the Messiah" (chevlei Mashiach) described the period of intensifying distress preceding the messianic age.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: The verb κηρυχθῆναι (kērychthēnai, aorist passive infinitive of κηρύσσω, G2784, "to herald, proclaim") indicates a completed proclamation that must occur before the consummation. The divine necessity (δεῖ, dei, "it is necessary") frames the global mission to all nations (πάντα τὰ ἔθνη) as part of God\'s decreed plan, not merely human initiative. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the Abrahamic promise that all nations would be blessed (Gen 12:3), now fulfilled through the gospel of the Christ.',
        14: 'GREEK: τὸ βδέλυγμα τῆς ἐρημώσεως (to bdelygma tēs erēmōseōs, "the abomination of desolation") directly echoes Daniel 9:27, 11:31, and 12:11 (LXX). The neuter noun βδέλυγμα unusually takes the masculine participle ἑστηκότα (hestēkota, "standing"), possibly personifying the abomination or pointing to a personal agent. HISTORICAL: The parenthetical "let the one who reads understand" (ὁ ἀναγινώσκων νοείτω) is a rare editorial aside in Mark, signaling that this prophecy demands careful interpretation by the reader/hearer of the text. The phrase recalls the desecration under Antiochus IV Epiphanes (1 Macc 1:54) as a type of a future desolation.',
        19: 'GREEK: θλῖψις (thlipsis, G2347) denotes pressing, crushing affliction. The phrase ἀπ\' ἀρχῆς κτίσεως ἣν ἔκτισεν ὁ θεός ("from the beginning of creation which God created") is unique to Mark and emphatically grounds the comparison in God\'s sovereign creative act. TYPOLOGY: The language echoes Daniel 12:1 (LXX), connecting this tribulation to the final distress prophesied by Daniel, after which Michael rises to deliver God\'s people.',
        22: 'GREEK: ψευδόχριστοι (pseudochristoi, G5580) and ψευδοπροφῆται (pseudoprophētai, G5578) are compound words—"false anointed ones" and "false prophets." The phrase εἰ δυνατόν ("if possible") implies a conditional that suggests God\'s protection over the elect, making their final deception ultimately impossible. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The capacity of false figures to produce σημεῖα καὶ τέρατα ("signs and wonders") echoes Deuteronomy 13:1-3, where God permits such signs as a test of loyalty to himself.',
        26: 'TYPOLOGY: τὸν υἱὸν τοῦ ἀνθρώπου ἐρχόμενον ἐν νεφέλαις ("the Son of Man coming in clouds") directly cites Daniel 7:13-14, where the "one like a son of man" approaches the Ancient of Days and receives dominion, glory, and an everlasting kingdom over all peoples, nations, and tongues. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In Daniel 7, the Son of Man figure receives authority in the heavenly court scene amid the divine council. Jesus identifies himself as this figure, the one enthroned above all heavenly powers. The μετὰ δυνάμεως πολλῆς καὶ δόξης ("with great power and glory") marks the visible vindication of the Christ before all creation.',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: ἐπισυνάξει (episynaxei, from ἐπισυνάγω, G1996, "to gather together upon") describes the eschatological ingathering of God\'s scattered people. TYPOLOGY: The gathering "from the four winds, from the end of the earth to the end of heaven" echoes Deuteronomy 30:4, Isaiah 11:11-12, and Zechariah 2:6, where God promises to regather Israel from the uttermost parts. The Christ fulfills the role of the Divine Shepherd-King who assembles his flock through his angelic hosts.',
        30: 'GREEK: γενεά (genea, G1074) can mean "generation" (a contemporaneous group), "race/people," or "age." The phrase οὐ μὴ παρέλθῃ (ou mē parelthē) is another emphatic double negative with aorist subjunctive—"shall by no means pass away." THEOLOGICAL: Interpreters debate whether "this generation" refers to Jesus\'s contemporaries (pointing to the AD 70 destruction as partial fulfillment), to the generation witnessing the final signs, or to the Jewish people as a whole enduring until the consummation. The juxtaposition with v.32 preserves the tension between certainty of fulfillment and unknowability of timing.',
        32: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is of profound Christological significance. The Son (ὁ υἱός, ho huios) places himself above the angels in the hierarchy of knowledge yet voluntarily subordinate to the Father regarding the appointed time. This reflects the incarnate Son\'s voluntary limitation within his earthly mission (cf. Phil 2:6-8), not an ontological deficiency. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The ranking—neither angels in heaven, nor the Son, except the Father—mirrors the heavenly hierarchy and underscores the Father\'s unique prerogative over eschatological timing.',
        37: 'GREEK: γρηγορεῖτε (grēgoreite, present active imperative of γρηγορέω, G1127, "keep watching, be wakeful") is the culminating command of the entire discourse. The shift from the private audience (v.3) to πᾶσιν (pasin, "to all") universalizes the imperative. STRUCTURE: This single imperative forms the rhetorical climax of Mark 13, gathering all the warnings (vv.5, 9, 23, 33, 35) into one final charge. The discourse that began with stones and buildings ends with a call to vigilant faithfulness.',
    },
    14: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Pascha" (πάσχα, Strong\'s G3957) is a transliteration of the Aramaic/Hebrew pesach (Passover). "Azuma" (ἄζυμα) refers to the Feast of Unleavened Bread, technically distinct but closely associated with Passover (Ex 12:15-20). "En dolō" (ἐν δόλῳ) — "by deceit/craft" — emphasizes the treachery of the plot. HISTORICAL: The Passover drew enormous crowds to Jerusalem, making the authorities fear a popular uprising on Jesus\' behalf.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The anointing of Jesus\' head echoes the anointing of kings in Israel (1 Sam 16:13; 1 Kgs 1:39). This woman unwittingly performs a prophetic act confirming Jesus as the Christos — the Anointed One — even as she simultaneously prepares his body for burial. GREEK: "Nardou pistikēs" (νάρδου πιστικῆς) — "pistikēs" is debated; it may mean "genuine/pure" or derive from the Sanskrit for spikenard. This is a near-hapax usage in the NT (cf. John 12:3).',
        8: 'GREEK: "Proelaben" (προέλαβεν, Strong\'s G4301) means "she came beforehand/anticipated" — a rare verb indicating prophetic timing. "Entaphiasmon" (ἐνταφιασμόν, Strong\'s G1780) refers specifically to burial preparation, used only here and in John 12:7 in the NT. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus reinterprets her act of devotion as an anointing for burial, linking his messianic identity inseparably with his coming death.',
        12: 'HISTORICAL: The Passover lamb was sacrificed on Nisan 14 in the afternoon at the temple. The question of chronology between Mark and John\'s accounts has generated extensive scholarly discussion. Mark presents the Last Supper as a Passover meal. GREEK: "Ethuon" (ἔθυον) — imperfect tense of "thyō" (to sacrifice/slaughter), indicating customary or ongoing action during the festival period.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Son of Man goes, just as it has been written concerning him" — Jesus affirms divine sovereignty over his passion while simultaneously holding the betrayer morally responsible. This tension between divine foreordination and human culpability is central to NT theology. TYPOLOGY: "Son of Man" (ho huios tou anthrōpou) alludes to Daniel 7:13-14, the heavenly figure who receives dominion from the Ancient of Days.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The institution of the Lord\'s Supper. "Touto estin to sōma mou" — "This is my body." Jesus reinterprets the Passover bread in terms of his own sacrificial death. TYPOLOGY: As the Passover lamb\'s body was broken for Israel\'s deliverance from Egypt (Ex 12), so Christ\'s body is given for the deliverance of many from sin. The bread of affliction (Deut 16:3) becomes the bread of new covenant life.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: "To haima mou tēs diathēkēs" — "my blood of the covenant" — directly echoes Moses\' words at Sinai: "Behold the blood of the covenant" (Ex 24:8, LXX). Jesus identifies himself as the mediator of a new covenant (Jer 31:31-34). "Ekchynnomenon hyper pollōn" — "being poured out on behalf of many" — echoes the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 53:12 who "poured out his soul to death" and "bore the sin of many." TYPOLOGY: The Passover blood on the doorposts (Ex 12:7, 13) finds its fulfillment in the blood of Christ poured out for the redemption of many.',
        27: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes Zechariah 13:7 (LXX), applying the striking of the shepherd and scattering of the flock to his own imminent arrest and the disciples\' flight. In Zechariah\'s context, this occurs in an eschatological passage about the purification of God\'s people. GREEK: "Skandalisthēsesthe" (σκανδαλισθήσεσθε) — from "skandalizō" (Strong\'s G4624), to cause to stumble or fall away, a theologically loaded term for apostasy under pressure.',
        33: 'GREEK: "Ekthambeisthai" (ἐκθαμβεῖσθαι, Strong\'s G1568) denotes extreme amazement or alarm — a strong word unique to Mark in the Gospels, suggesting overwhelming horror and dread. "Adēmonein" (ἀδημονεῖν, Strong\'s G85) conveys deep distress and anguish, possibly from a root meaning "away from home" — a profound existential disorientation. THEOLOGICAL: These terms reveal the full humanity of the incarnate Son facing the weight of the coming atonement.',
        36: 'GREEK: "Abba" (Ἀββά) is an Aramaic term of intimate address for "Father," preserved untranslated and then glossed with the Greek "ho patēr." This is one of the rare instances where Jesus\' original Aramaic is preserved in the text (cf. Rom 8:15; Gal 4:6). THEOLOGICAL: The cup is a well-known OT metaphor for divine wrath and judgment (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17, 22; Jer 25:15). Jesus\' prayer reveals both his fully human shrinking from the cross and his perfect obedience to the Father\'s will.',
        38: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak" — "pneuma" (πνεῦμα) here refers to the human spirit or inner resolve, contrasted with "sarx" (σάρξ), the mortal human nature prone to frailty. This is not a Gnostic dualism but an acknowledgment of human limitation that requires dependence on God through prayer. GREEK: "Prothymon" (πρόθυμον, Strong\'s G4289) means "eager, willing, ready" — literally "forward in spirit."',
        41: 'GREEK: "Apechei" (ἀπέχει) is a notoriously difficult term here. It may mean "it is enough," "it is settled," or could be a commercial term meaning "the account is closed / paid in full." Some manuscripts read it as an impersonal verb. THEOLOGICAL: "The Son of Man is being betrayed into the hands of sinners" — the divine passive ("paradidotai") suggests God\'s sovereign hand behind even the act of betrayal, fulfilling the Scriptures (v. 49).',
        49: 'TYPOLOGY: "Let the Scriptures be fulfilled" — Jesus interprets his arrest as the fulfillment of prophetic Scripture, likely encompassing Isaiah 53, Psalm 22, Zechariah 13:7 (already cited in v. 27), and Daniel 7. The entire passion narrative is framed as the outworking of God\'s redemptive plan revealed in the OT. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' appeal to Scripture even in the moment of his arrest demonstrates his understanding of his messianic mission as defined by the written Word of God.',
        51: 'HISTORICAL: The identity of this young man (neaniskos) is debated. An ancient tradition associates him with John Mark himself, the author of this Gospel, which would explain why only Mark includes this vivid detail. The linen cloth (sindōn) may foreshadow the burial linen of 15:46. GREEK: "Sindona" (σινδόνα, Strong\'s G4616) refers to a fine linen garment, the same word used for Jesus\' burial shroud.',
        58: 'THEOLOGICAL: The false testimony distorts something Jesus actually said (John 2:19-21). Jesus spoke of the temple of his body; the witnesses twist it into a threat against the physical temple. TYPOLOGY: The irony is profound — Jesus\' body (the true temple, the dwelling place of God) will indeed be destroyed and raised in three days. The "temple not made with hands" (acheiropoiēton) points to the resurrection body and the new temple reality of the church (1 Cor 3:16; 2 Cor 5:1).',
        61: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Are you the Christ, the Son of the Blessed One?" — The high priest combines two messianic titles. "The Blessed One" (ho eulogētos) is a Jewish circumlocution for God, making this question about divine sonship, not merely messianic office. Jesus\' silence before this point fulfills Isaiah 53:7: "like a sheep before its shearers is silent." GREEK: "Esiōpa" (ἐσιώπα) is the imperfect tense — he kept on being silent — emphasizing the sustained and deliberate nature of his refusal to answer.',
        62: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Egō eimi" — "I am" — Jesus\' unequivocal affirmation, possibly echoing the divine self-identification of Exodus 3:14 (LXX). He then combines Daniel 7:13 (the Son of Man coming with clouds) with Psalm 110:1 (sitting at the right hand), claiming both heavenly enthronement and eschatological authority. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Jesus identifies himself as the Daniel 7 Son of Man who approaches the Ancient of Days and receives dominion, glory, and kingdom — the one seated at the right hand of "the Power" (tēs dynameōs), another circumlocution for God. This is the climactic christological declaration in Mark\'s Gospel.',
        64: 'GREEK: "Enochon" (ἔνοχον, Strong\'s G1777) means "liable to, deserving of, guilty of" — a legal term. "Thanatou" (θανάτου) is a genitive of penalty: "deserving of death." HISTORICAL: Under Jewish law, blasphemy was punishable by death (Lev 24:16). The Sanhedrin judged Jesus\' claim to be the Son of God seated at God\'s right hand as blasphemous usurpation of divine prerogative. Ironically, their verdict condemns the very one who truly holds the authority he claimed.',
        72: 'GREEK: "Epibalōn" (ἐπιβαλών) is a difficult participial form. Possible meanings include "having thrown himself down," "having cast his mind upon it," or "having broken down" in weeping. The ambiguity has generated much scholarly discussion. TYPOLOGY: Peter\'s triple denial corresponds to his later triple restoration by the risen Jesus (John 21:15-17). The cock crowing twice, unique to Mark\'s account, may reflect Peter\'s own vivid memory as the source behind Mark\'s Gospel. THEOLOGICAL: Peter\'s failure demonstrates that even the most zealous human resolve ("If I must die with you, I will not deny you," v. 31) cannot withstand the hour of testing without divine empowerment — precisely the warning of verse 38.',
    },
    15: {
        1: 'GREEK: συμβούλιον (symboulion, G4824) denotes a formal consultation or council decision, not a casual meeting. The phrase πρωΐ (prōi, "early morning") indicates this was a dawn session of the Sanhedrin to formalize the nighttime trial verdict. HISTORICAL: Roman law required capital cases to be heard in daylight, necessitating this early morning ratification before bringing Jesus to Pilate.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: Pilate\'s question "You are the King of the Jews?" uses σύ (sy) emphatically—"You, you are the King?" Jesus\' response σὺ λέγεις ("You say it") is an affirmative that redirects the authority of the declaration back onto Pilate. Jesus affirms his kingship while revealing Pilate speaks truth he does not fully comprehend. TYPOLOGY: The true King stands before earthly authority, echoing the pattern of Joseph before Pharaoh and Daniel before Nebuchadnezzar.',
        7: 'GREEK: στασιαστῶν (stasiastōn, G4955) is a NT hapax legomenon, meaning "insurrectionists" or "rebels." Barabbas (Βαραββᾶς, "son of the father") was a political revolutionary and murderer. THEOLOGICAL: The irony is profound—the crowd chooses a false "son of the father" who brings death over the true Son of the Father who brings life.',
        15: 'GREEK: φραγελλώσας (phragellōsas, G5417) refers to the Roman flagellum, a scourging with leather thongs embedded with bone and metal—a punishment that often killed. THEOLOGICAL: Pilate\'s attempt to satisfy (τὸ ἱκανὸν ποιῆσαι) the crowd reveals the moral bankruptcy of political expediency. The innocent is scourged while the guilty goes free—the substitutionary pattern is unmistakable. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the Day of Atonement pattern (Lev 16): one is released (Barabbas, the scapegoat) while the other bears the penalty (Isa 53:5).',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: The πορφύρα (porphyra, "purple") and ἀκάνθινον στέφανον (akanthinon stephanon, "crown of thorns") are meant as mockery but carry profound typological weight. Purple is the color of royalty; the thorns recall the curse on the ground in Genesis 3:18. The true King wears the curse of Eden as his crown. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The soldiers unknowingly enthrone the King of kings, paralleling how the hostile nations rage against the Lord\'s Anointed (Ps 2:1-4).',
        24: 'TYPOLOGY: The dividing of garments and casting of lots is a direct fulfillment of Psalm 22:18 (LXX Ps 21:19): "They divided my garments among themselves, and upon my clothing they cast lots." Mark expects the reader to recognize the entire Psalm 22 framework as governing this narrative. GREEK: διαμερίζονται (diamerizontai) is a present tense, creating vivid narrative immediacy—"they are dividing."',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: The ἐπιγραφή (epigraphē, "inscription") of the αἰτία (aitia, "charge") reads Ὁ βασιλεὺς τῶν Ἰουδαίων—"The King of the Jews." Meant as the legal accusation of sedition, it is in fact the truest theological statement: Jesus is indeed the King of the Jews and of all nations. What Rome writes in condemnation, heaven writes in proclamation.',
        33: 'THEOLOGICAL: The σκότος (skotos, "darkness") from the sixth to ninth hour (noon to 3 PM) over ὅλην τὴν γῆν ("the whole land/earth") echoes the plague of darkness in Exodus 10:22 and the prophetic language of Amos 8:9: "I will make the sun go down at noon and darken the earth in broad daylight." TYPOLOGY: Cosmic darkness at creation\'s center signals a new-exodus event: the final Passover Lamb is being slain.',
        34: 'GREEK: Ἐλωΐ ἐλωΐ λεμὰ σαβαχθάνι is Aramaic (with some Hebrew influence), transliterated from the opening of Psalm 22:1 (LXX Ps 21:2). Mark provides the Greek translation: Ὁ θεός μου ὁ θεός μου, εἰς τί ἐγκατέλιπές με. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus quotes the Psalm as one who enters fully into the experience of godforsakenness on behalf of sinful humanity. Yet Psalm 22 moves from lament to triumphant vindication (Ps 22:22-31), and the cry is not despair but the voice of the righteous sufferer who trusts God even in abandonment. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Son addresses the Father with the covenant cry "my God," maintaining the relationship even in the moment of judicial separation.',
        37: 'GREEK: ἐξέπνευσεν (exepneusen, G1606) literally means "he breathed out"—a stark, clinical term for death. The phrase ἀφεὶς φωνὴν μεγάλην ("having let out a great voice/cry") suggests a powerful final utterance, not the whimper of an exhausted victim. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus does not have his life taken from him; he releases it with sovereign authority (cf. John 10:18). The loud cry at death was noted as unusual for crucifixion victims, who typically died of slow asphyxiation.',
        38: 'GREEK: καταπέτασμα (katapetasma, G2665) refers to the inner veil of the temple separating the Holy Place from the Holy of Holies. THEOLOGICAL: The tearing (ἐσχίσθη, passive voice—God is the implied agent) from top (ἄνωθεν, "from above") to bottom signifies divine action opening access to God\'s presence. TYPOLOGY: The veil represented the barrier between God and humanity (Exod 26:33; Heb 10:19-20). Its rending at the moment of Jesus\' death declares that through his sacrifice the way into the heavenly Holy of Holies is now opened. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The throne room of God is laid bare—what was guarded by cherubim since Eden (Gen 3:24) is now accessible through the body of Christ.',
        39: 'THEOLOGICAL: The centurion (κεντυρίων, a Latin loanword) is the first human in Mark\'s Gospel to confess Jesus as υἱὸς θεοῦ ("Son of God") after his death. This is the climactic christological confession of the Gospel. Notably it comes from a Gentile, not from Israel\'s leaders—foreshadowing the gospel\'s movement to the nations. STRUCTURE: This confession forms an inclusio with Mark 1:1 ("the beginning of the gospel of Jesus Christ, Son of God"), bracketing the entire Gospel narrative.',
        43: 'GREEK: εὐσχήμων βουλευτής (euschēmōn bouleutēs) means "prominent/honorable councilor," indicating Joseph was a member of the Sanhedrin itself. HISTORICAL: τολμήσας (tolmēsas, "having taken courage/daring") reveals the risk: requesting the body of a condemned criminal from the Roman governor required extraordinary boldness, especially for a council member whose colleagues had just condemned Jesus. THEOLOGICAL: Joseph was προσδεχόμενος τὴν βασιλείαν τοῦ θεοῦ ("awaiting the kingdom of God")—he recognized in the crucified Jesus the hope of Israel\'s restoration.',
        46: 'HISTORICAL: The σινδών (sindōn, G4616) was a fine linen cloth, used for burial shrouds among the wealthy. The tomb hewn from rock (λελατομημένον ἐκ πέτρας) was a costly, new burial site. TYPOLOGY: The stone rolled against the door echoes the sealing of the den in Daniel 6:17. As Daniel emerged alive, so will the Son of Man. The burial in a rich man\'s tomb fulfills Isaiah 53:9: "His grave was assigned with the rich."',
    },
    16: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Diagenomenou" (διαγενομένου) is a genitive absolute participle from diaginomai (Strong\'s G1230), meaning "having passed" or "having elapsed." The spices (arōmata, G759) were purchased after Sabbath ended at sundown Saturday, indicating the women observed Sabbath rest (cf. Luke 23:56). HISTORICAL: Anointing the dead was a customary Jewish burial practice; the hasty Friday burial before Sabbath left this duty incomplete.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Neaniskon" (νεανίσκον, G3495) means "young man," yet the white robe (stolēn leukēn) and the reaction of astonishment (exethambēthēsan, G1568) indicate an angelic figure. Matthew 28:2-5 explicitly identifies this figure as an angel. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Angels as heavenly messengers clothed in white appear throughout Scripture as members of God\'s divine council dispatched to announce his decrees (cf. Dan 10:5-6; Acts 1:10).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The passive "ēgerthē" (ἠγέρθη, G1453) — "he has been raised" — is a divine passive, indicating God the Father as the agent of resurrection. This is the climactic declaration of Mark\'s Gospel: the crucified Nazarene lives. TYPOLOGY: The empty tomb fulfills Jesus\' own threefold passion predictions (Mark 8:31; 9:31; 10:34) and echoes the pattern of divine deliverance from Sheol in the Psalms (Ps 16:10).',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The singling out of Peter ("and Peter") after his threefold denial (Mark 14:66-72) reveals a deliberate message of restoration and grace. Jesus does not abandon the one who denied him. GREEK: "Proagei" (προάγει, G4254), "he goes before," is a present tense indicating Jesus as the shepherd who leads his flock (cf. Mark 14:28; John 10:4).',
        8: 'STRUCTURE: Many scholars regard verse 8 as the original ending of Mark\'s Gospel, with "ephobounto gar" (ἐφοβοῦντο γάρ, "for they were afraid") forming a strikingly abrupt conclusion. The shorter ending in brackets (⟦...⟧) appears in a few later manuscripts but is widely considered a later scribal addition to soften this abruptness. GREEK: "Tromos" (τρόμος, G5156) and "ekstasis" (ἔκστασις, G1611) together convey trembling and a state of being beside oneself — the proper human response to divine theophany.',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: Verses 9-20 constitute the so-called "Longer Ending of Mark," absent from the earliest and most reliable manuscripts (Codex Sinaiticus, Codex Vaticanus) and noted as secondary by early Church fathers including Eusebius and Jerome. Nevertheless, the passage was received into the canonical tradition at an early date. GREEK: "Anastas" (ἀναστάς, G450) — "having risen" — is the same resurrection vocabulary used throughout the NT kerygma.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The Great Commission in Mark\'s form uses "ktisis" (κτίσις, G2937), meaning "creation" — the gospel is to be proclaimed not merely to all nations but to "all creation," reflecting the cosmic scope of Christ\'s lordship and redemption (cf. Rom 8:19-22; Col 1:15-20). GREEK: "Kēryxate" (κηρύξατε, G2784) is an aorist imperative — a decisive, urgent command to herald the good news as a royal proclamation.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' session "at the right hand of God" (ek dexiōn tou theou) is a direct fulfillment of Psalm 110:1 (LXX Ps 109:1): "Sit at my right hand." This is the most frequently cited OT text in the NT, establishing Christ\'s sovereign enthronement as King over all powers. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The ascension and enthronement place the risen Christ above all heavenly authorities in the divine council (cf. Eph 1:20-21; Phil 2:9-11; Heb 1:3, 13).',
        20: 'GREEK: "Synergountos" (συνεργοῦντος, G4903) — "working together with" — indicates the Lord\'s ongoing active partnership with his apostles. "Bebaiountos" (βεβαιοῦντος, G950) means "confirming" or "establishing as legally valid." THEOLOGICAL: The signs (sēmeiōn, G4592) serve not as ends in themselves but as divine confirmation that the proclaimed word carries the authority of the enthroned Lord. The Gospel thus closes not with a static ending but with an open, expanding mission.',
    },
}